TY  - JOUR
AB  - An index of agricultural purchasing power may be used to study the effect of agriculture on business cycles. Reasons for the importance of this index. The physical volume of production is in large part determined by agricultural production. Explanation of the correlation between volume of industrial production and the wholesale price level. The role of speculation and bank credit. The rate of interest a function of gold movement and the demand for funds. The demand for funds may be measured roughly by agricultural purchasing power, because the latter reflects the volume of both industrial and agricultural production. Stock of gold is negatively correlated with agricultural purchasing power. This may be explained by a synthesis of other correlations which requires the volume of industrial production to be negatively correlated with net exports of merchandise. This logical requirements is verified by direct comparison of net exports and industrial production. Conclusion: business cycles are initiated by the vicissitudes of agriculture; but the translation of agricultural irregularities to business is governed by non-agricultural factors of an institutional nature.
AU  - Anderson, Montgomery D.
